00:00:01.397 --> 00:00:02.730
FEMALE SPEAKER: Hello, everyone.

00:00:02.730 --> 00:00:03.854
Welcome to Talks at Google.

00:00:03.854 --> 00:00:05.700
Today it's my absolute
pleasure to welcome

00:00:05.700 --> 00:00:08.540
Mars Hallman, the winner
of the 2015 GLSEN Respect

00:00:08.540 --> 00:00:10.620
Award for the Student
Advocate of the Year.

00:00:10.620 --> 00:00:12.460
And Stephanie
Frosch, who you might

00:00:12.460 --> 00:00:14.760
know as ElloSteph from YouTube.

00:00:14.760 --> 00:00:16.129
Thanks both for being here.

00:00:16.129 --> 00:00:17.206
STEPHANIE FROSCH: Thank
you for having us.

00:00:17.206 --> 00:00:18.622
FEMALE SPEAKER:
Round of applause.

00:00:18.622 --> 00:00:20.400
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:20.400 --> 00:00:24.020
So I'm going to start off by
talking about gender pronouns,

00:00:24.020 --> 00:00:26.580
because that's what one does.

00:00:26.580 --> 00:00:29.252
I think it's an important thing,
because I think it's something

00:00:29.252 --> 00:00:31.710
that maybe the public doesn't
always wrap their head around

00:00:31.710 --> 00:00:34.810
easily, but it's important
to the people who

00:00:34.810 --> 00:00:36.590
want to be identified
maybe not as "he,"

00:00:36.590 --> 00:00:37.930
"she," or anything in between.

00:00:37.930 --> 00:00:40.110
So Mars, I'm going to
let you take this one.

00:00:40.110 --> 00:00:41.526
Can you explain
to us a little bit

00:00:41.526 --> 00:00:43.250
about how you prefer
to be referred to?

00:00:43.250 --> 00:00:44.640
And the reasoning for that?

00:00:44.640 --> 00:00:45.260
MARS HALLMAN: All right.

00:00:45.260 --> 00:00:46.843
I use the pronouns
"they," "them," and

00:00:46.843 --> 00:00:49.230
"theirs," because they
don't have the gender

00:00:49.230 --> 00:00:51.689
connotation of "he," "him,"
"his," or "she," "her," "hers."

00:00:51.689 --> 00:00:54.188
And you use it in the same way
you would if you were talking

00:00:54.188 --> 00:00:55.340
in the third person plural.

00:00:55.340 --> 00:00:56.874
It's very simple.

00:00:56.874 --> 00:00:58.790
FEMALE SPEAKER: And the
reasoning for that is?

00:00:58.790 --> 00:00:59.480
MARS HALLMAN: They're
important to me.

00:00:59.480 --> 00:01:00.830
I'm non-binary.

00:01:00.830 --> 00:01:04.234
And they reaffirm my gender
identity when people use them.

00:01:04.234 --> 00:01:06.650
FEMALE SPEAKER: And just can
you explain what "non-binary"

00:01:06.650 --> 00:01:08.471
is for our viewers out there.

00:01:08.471 --> 00:01:10.470
MARS HALLMAN: I'm not a
boy, and I'm not a girl,

00:01:10.470 --> 00:01:12.380
and I'm not anything in between.

00:01:12.380 --> 00:01:14.410
FEMALE SPEAKER: Wonderful.

00:01:14.410 --> 00:01:17.120
So Mars, you are the Student
Advocate of the Year.

00:01:17.120 --> 00:01:20.790
Can you talk about what some
of the process of becoming

00:01:20.790 --> 00:01:25.680
an advocate for the LGBTQ,
everyone in-between, community

00:01:25.680 --> 00:01:26.920
was like for you?

00:01:26.920 --> 00:01:30.670
MARS HALLMAN: Well, my process
was being the Q in LGBTQ.

00:01:30.670 --> 00:01:35.644
Growing up as the Q, you see a
lot of bullying and inequality

00:01:35.644 --> 00:01:38.060
and harassment, and you see
that happening to your friends

00:01:38.060 --> 00:01:39.640
and to yourself.

00:01:39.640 --> 00:01:43.750
And you grow up and you
become strong from that,

00:01:43.750 --> 00:01:47.260
and you-- I grew up having the
privilege of having parents who

00:01:47.260 --> 00:01:49.010
support me and having
a safe place at home

00:01:49.010 --> 00:01:50.810
knowing my friends
don't have that.

00:01:50.810 --> 00:01:52.577
I know that school
and the workplace

00:01:52.577 --> 00:01:54.660
are the places that are
going to be safe for them.

00:01:54.660 --> 00:01:57.872
So I know that I have to make
those places safe for them.

00:01:57.872 --> 00:02:00.080
FEMALE SPEAKER: And you led
an effort at your school,

00:02:00.080 --> 00:02:01.610
in particular, to
kind of make sure

00:02:01.610 --> 00:02:04.950
that there were
bathrooms that were

00:02:04.950 --> 00:02:06.490
appropriate for
anybody who didn't

00:02:06.490 --> 00:02:07.782
want to identify as either one.

00:02:07.782 --> 00:02:09.573
Can you talk about some
of the other things

00:02:09.573 --> 00:02:11.920
that you kind of took
care of along the way that

00:02:11.920 --> 00:02:13.829
helped create this safe space?

00:02:13.829 --> 00:02:16.120
MARS HALLMAN: Well, I started
the Gay-Straight Alliance

00:02:16.120 --> 00:02:17.870
at my school, the first
one in the region.

00:02:17.870 --> 00:02:19.194
Woo.

00:02:19.194 --> 00:02:20.300
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:22.160 --> 00:02:25.860
And that itself was a struggle.

00:02:25.860 --> 00:02:30.190
Getting support from local
parents wasn't going to happen,

00:02:30.190 --> 00:02:32.290
so we got a sponsor.

00:02:32.290 --> 00:02:34.460
I spoke myself to the principal.

00:02:34.460 --> 00:02:36.920
I got the resources from GLSEN
and from the Gay-Straight

00:02:36.920 --> 00:02:40.750
Alliance Network and
proposed the club.

00:02:40.750 --> 00:02:46.230
And it was deferred to a
school board meeting decision,

00:02:46.230 --> 00:02:48.940
which was then deferred.

00:02:48.940 --> 00:02:50.700
And they announced
through the paper

00:02:50.700 --> 00:02:52.089
that it was going to be allowed.

00:02:52.089 --> 00:02:53.630
So the Gay-Straight
Alliance started.

00:02:53.630 --> 00:02:56.180
We had our first
meetings recently.

00:02:56.180 --> 00:02:58.030
Actually, at the
start of Ally Week.

00:02:58.030 --> 00:02:58.800
FEMALE SPEAKER: Congratulations.

00:02:58.800 --> 00:02:59.716
STEPHANIE FROSCH: Wow.

00:02:59.716 --> 00:03:02.430
MARS HALLMAN: So so far we've
the worked on educating people

00:03:02.430 --> 00:03:05.070
on gender pronouns,
gender identities,

00:03:05.070 --> 00:03:07.531
and done some just fun
activities making sure everyone

00:03:07.531 --> 00:03:10.030
knows that they're welcome at
school no matter who they are.

00:03:10.030 --> 00:03:11.350
FEMALE SPEAKER: Awesome.

00:03:11.350 --> 00:03:14.210
Steph, you have a larger
kind of platform to use.

00:03:14.210 --> 00:03:16.152
You are a YouTube sensation.

00:03:16.152 --> 00:03:17.610
STEPHANIE FROSCH:
I do the YouTube.

00:03:17.610 --> 00:03:19.780
FEMALE SPEAKER:
You do the YouTube.

00:03:19.780 --> 00:03:22.120
Could you talk to us
about-- you definitely bring

00:03:22.120 --> 00:03:24.570
kind of a positive air
and, like, an air of humor

00:03:24.570 --> 00:03:27.570
to these issues that
I think we need.

00:03:27.570 --> 00:03:29.930
You know, I think if
you get too caught

00:03:29.930 --> 00:03:33.302
in the they're serious
issues, they're

00:03:33.302 --> 00:03:34.760
kind of sometimes
upsetting issues,

00:03:34.760 --> 00:03:36.950
but you bring this very,
like, hey, it's OK.

00:03:36.950 --> 00:03:37.450
It's fine.

00:03:37.450 --> 00:03:38.344
It's fun.

00:03:38.344 --> 00:03:40.510
Can you talk about kind of
the process of developing

00:03:40.510 --> 00:03:42.137
your voice online?

00:03:42.137 --> 00:03:43.720
STEPHANIE FROSCH:
Well, I started when

00:03:43.720 --> 00:03:45.510
I was in high school on Tumblr.

00:03:45.510 --> 00:03:47.730
And the reason why my
Tumblr sort of grew

00:03:47.730 --> 00:03:49.860
was because at the
time it was very rare

00:03:49.860 --> 00:03:54.160
finding a feminine lesbian
on the internet at my age.

00:03:54.160 --> 00:03:56.290
I mean, this is 2011,
but at the same time,

00:03:56.290 --> 00:03:58.650
it was like finding
a shiny Pokemon.

00:03:58.650 --> 00:04:01.340
So that's how I grew
my audience on Tumblr.

00:04:01.340 --> 00:04:03.076
And from there, I
would just write.

00:04:03.076 --> 00:04:04.950
I was very big into
writing, but eventually I

00:04:04.950 --> 00:04:07.750
had a fan say, I really
love what you write,

00:04:07.750 --> 00:04:08.652
but I hate reading.

00:04:08.652 --> 00:04:09.610
Could you make a video?

00:04:09.610 --> 00:04:11.710
And I was like, I have
all this free time.

00:04:11.710 --> 00:04:12.340
Why not?

00:04:12.340 --> 00:04:15.220
So not having a life
actually paid off.

00:04:15.220 --> 00:04:16.970
And it just kind
of grew from there.

00:04:16.970 --> 00:04:19.719
And I realized that I started
getting more serious questions

00:04:19.719 --> 00:04:21.510
in regards to being
kicked out of your home

00:04:21.510 --> 00:04:24.050
to things like wanting
to commit suicide.

00:04:24.050 --> 00:04:27.554
And from there I wanted to be
more certified to answer those

00:04:27.554 --> 00:04:29.220
questions, because I
felt like I wasn't.

00:04:29.220 --> 00:04:31.920
So I got my certification
in suicide prevention.

00:04:31.920 --> 00:04:35.830
And I was on the board
for LGBTQ+ services

00:04:35.830 --> 00:04:36.710
at my university.

00:04:36.710 --> 00:04:38.410
And from there I
was like, how can I

00:04:38.410 --> 00:04:41.432
include entertainment
and these issues

00:04:41.432 --> 00:04:42.640
that I'm so passionate about?

00:04:42.640 --> 00:04:46.200
So a way that I see it is
like dipping a broccoli

00:04:46.200 --> 00:04:46.980
in chocolate.

00:04:46.980 --> 00:04:48.920
So one of my most
successful videos,

00:04:48.920 --> 00:04:51.410
which is about
gender recognition

00:04:51.410 --> 00:04:53.868
and sexuality recognition, is
called "Never Have I Ever,"

00:04:53.868 --> 00:04:55.826
which, you know, that
popular game "never, ever

00:04:55.826 --> 00:04:56.590
have I done this."

00:04:56.590 --> 00:04:58.912
So it starts out
fun and cheerful,

00:04:58.912 --> 00:05:00.620
and then it gets into
more serious issues

00:05:00.620 --> 00:05:01.510
with the statistics.

00:05:01.510 --> 00:05:02.885
So I'm like, if
I can get someone

00:05:02.885 --> 00:05:06.480
to watch something and be
intrigued by it while still

00:05:06.480 --> 00:05:08.565
learning and keeping
it at a lighter note,

00:05:08.565 --> 00:05:10.690
then I feel like you're
more likely to take that in

00:05:10.690 --> 00:05:12.050
and more likely to be accepting.

00:05:12.050 --> 00:05:13.650
And it's how we learn.

00:05:13.650 --> 00:05:14.990
It's how we process.

00:05:14.990 --> 00:05:17.760
But always in school,
you want to get an A

00:05:17.760 --> 00:05:20.030
because the teacher
then congratulates you

00:05:20.030 --> 00:05:21.770
not because the
teacher puts you down

00:05:21.770 --> 00:05:23.050
for getting the answer wrong.

00:05:23.050 --> 00:05:24.740
So I feel like that's
how society is.

00:05:24.740 --> 00:05:26.740
FEMALE SPEAKER: It's very
carrot, not the stick.

00:05:26.740 --> 00:05:27.699
STEPHANIE FROSCH: Yeah.

00:05:27.699 --> 00:05:29.406
FEMALE SPEAKER: You
made an amazing point

00:05:29.406 --> 00:05:31.920
where we do live in this kind
of wonderful era where maybe,

00:05:31.920 --> 00:05:34.850
apparently even
four years ago, it's

00:05:34.850 --> 00:05:36.712
tough to find someone
who maybe identifies

00:05:36.712 --> 00:05:37.670
in the same way you do.

00:05:37.670 --> 00:05:40.870
You know, we're all individuals,
we're all different,

00:05:40.870 --> 00:05:42.709
but if you grew up in
a small town, maybe,

00:05:42.709 --> 00:05:44.500
you don't necessarily
have those resources.

00:05:44.500 --> 00:05:45.320
STEPHANIE FROSCH: Yeah.

00:05:45.320 --> 00:05:46.736
FEMALE SPEAKER:
But, Mars, for you

00:05:46.736 --> 00:05:49.340
was the internet kind of playing
a role in your support system

00:05:49.340 --> 00:05:51.670
and kind of getting your
efforts off the ground?

00:05:51.670 --> 00:05:54.489
MARS HALLMAN: Yes.

00:05:54.489 --> 00:05:56.030
The internet is
where I first learned

00:05:56.030 --> 00:05:59.370
about queer and
transgender issues

00:05:59.370 --> 00:06:01.845
through just various support
groups and just databases.

00:06:01.845 --> 00:06:05.210
Just learning statistics.

00:06:05.210 --> 00:06:07.270
I contacted the Gay-Straight
Alliance Network

00:06:07.270 --> 00:06:08.280
through the internet.

00:06:08.280 --> 00:06:09.900
A lot of Google searching.

00:06:09.900 --> 00:06:13.680
And that's how I got in contact
with Anna Davis and Chris

00:06:13.680 --> 00:06:16.730
Hampton of the
ACLU, and that was

00:06:16.730 --> 00:06:18.980
where we got a lot of the
support for getting the GSA.

00:06:18.980 --> 00:06:21.232
And just for learning
that it's OK to be me.

00:06:21.232 --> 00:06:22.940
FEMALE SPEAKER: Steph,
I think that's one

00:06:22.940 --> 00:06:24.825
of the things you kind of
touch on in most of your videos

00:06:24.825 --> 00:06:25.620
is like, it's OK to be you.

00:06:25.620 --> 00:06:26.552
It's OK to be whatever.

00:06:26.552 --> 00:06:28.927
STEPHANIE FROSCH: Yeah, because
oftentimes in small towns

00:06:28.927 --> 00:06:31.080
you don't have that
reassurance that it's OK.

00:06:31.080 --> 00:06:33.820
And the internet is an
amazing outreach for that.

00:06:33.820 --> 00:06:37.050
I mean, I went to a
religious private school

00:06:37.050 --> 00:06:39.000
from kindergarten
to senior year,

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:41.120
or as I like to call
it "Jew school."

00:06:41.120 --> 00:06:43.220
And it was great,
but at the same time,

00:06:43.220 --> 00:06:47.070
I was the only a LGBTQ+
identified person.

00:06:47.070 --> 00:06:49.390
So I had no resources.

00:06:49.390 --> 00:06:51.150
I had no one to go to.

00:06:51.150 --> 00:06:53.920
But by simply typing
something into the internet,

00:06:53.920 --> 00:06:54.840
I had a community.

00:06:54.840 --> 00:06:55.690
I had the support.

00:06:55.690 --> 00:06:56.540
I had the outreach.

00:06:56.540 --> 00:06:59.240
And I feel like that's so
important for Millennials

00:06:59.240 --> 00:07:01.820
and the new generations
today is we're so

00:07:01.820 --> 00:07:05.312
connected now that no one
has to be alone anymore.

00:07:05.312 --> 00:07:07.520
FEMALE SPEAKER: Is that--
what's one thing you really

00:07:07.520 --> 00:07:09.660
hope that your audience
takes away from your videos?

00:07:09.660 --> 00:07:11.160
Is it that is that
you're not alone?

00:07:11.160 --> 00:07:11.860
Is it--

00:07:11.860 --> 00:07:12.370
STEPHANIE FROSCH:
It's definitely

00:07:12.370 --> 00:07:14.470
that they're not alone
and definitely how

00:07:14.470 --> 00:07:17.080
not everything in society
needs to be a taboo subject.

00:07:17.080 --> 00:07:21.070
I mean, even back in the day,
my first college roommate

00:07:21.070 --> 00:07:24.136
was gender non-binary, and
they weren't comfortable even

00:07:24.136 --> 00:07:26.010
bringing it up in
conversation because people

00:07:26.010 --> 00:07:27.270
weren't talking about it.

00:07:27.270 --> 00:07:29.250
And I feel like the
more we talk about it

00:07:29.250 --> 00:07:32.220
and say it's OK to talk about
it, the less of a "big deal"

00:07:32.220 --> 00:07:33.030
it's going to be.

00:07:33.030 --> 00:07:35.070
It's going to be, oh,
these are your pronouns?

00:07:35.070 --> 00:07:35.580
Yeah?

00:07:35.580 --> 00:07:36.579
Those are your pronouns.

00:07:36.579 --> 00:07:37.960
Versus what is this?

00:07:37.960 --> 00:07:40.540
And then making
a big deal of it.

00:07:40.540 --> 00:07:42.500
FEMALE SPEAKER: Mars,
you said something

00:07:42.500 --> 00:07:44.360
earlier that I enjoyed.

00:07:44.360 --> 00:07:46.361
And you said, like,
Nashville isn't a bad place.

00:07:46.361 --> 00:07:47.860
And could you talk
a little bit more

00:07:47.860 --> 00:07:49.870
about that in terms of,
like, finding acceptance

00:07:49.870 --> 00:07:53.567
in the real world space
versus the internet?

00:07:53.567 --> 00:07:56.150
MARS HALLMAN: Well, I grew up
in a few different environments.

00:07:56.150 --> 00:07:58.730
I had a kind of a city
upbringing and a country

00:07:58.730 --> 00:07:59.580
upbringing.

00:07:59.580 --> 00:08:03.370
And then we moved to Nashville
a few years ago on purpose.

00:08:03.370 --> 00:08:04.760
We didn't think, oh, no.

00:08:04.760 --> 00:08:07.400
We've ended up in the
middle of nowhere.

00:08:07.400 --> 00:08:08.430
What will we do?

00:08:08.430 --> 00:08:10.630
There's a really
great community there

00:08:10.630 --> 00:08:16.460
with some very vocal people
who would oppose change.

00:08:16.460 --> 00:08:20.800
But also, when I started the GSA
and when I started campaigning

00:08:20.800 --> 00:08:23.820
for equality in my school,
lots of adult allies,

00:08:23.820 --> 00:08:26.460
either from Nashville or who
still lived there or had moved

00:08:26.460 --> 00:08:29.940
away, came to me and
my mother with messages

00:08:29.940 --> 00:08:31.770
of support or thanks.

00:08:31.770 --> 00:08:34.840
Some of them would send monetary
contributions to the GSA,

00:08:34.840 --> 00:08:39.400
some of them would send their
words and their stories.

00:08:39.400 --> 00:08:43.385
So it's a good town
with good people.

00:08:43.385 --> 00:08:44.260
FEMALE SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:08:44.260 --> 00:08:45.010
It's good to know.

00:08:45.010 --> 00:08:48.330
It's good to know that there's
support when you asked for it.

00:08:48.330 --> 00:08:51.704
I'd love to know-- this
is not-- unfortunately

00:08:51.704 --> 00:08:53.370
the internet is a
very supportive place,

00:08:53.370 --> 00:08:54.911
but the internet
can also be somewhat

00:08:54.911 --> 00:08:57.090
of a disrespectful place.

00:08:57.090 --> 00:08:59.120
And I think you both
probably deal very well

00:08:59.120 --> 00:09:01.199
with those types
of comments and are

00:09:01.199 --> 00:09:02.490
able to kind of brush them off.

00:09:02.490 --> 00:09:03.680
And what's some
advice you'd give

00:09:03.680 --> 00:09:05.240
to people who are
kind of dealing

00:09:05.240 --> 00:09:07.735
with the trolls of the internet?

00:09:07.735 --> 00:09:09.110
STEPHANIE FROSCH:
I mean, the way

00:09:09.110 --> 00:09:12.930
I see it, in life in general
you can't please everyone,

00:09:12.930 --> 00:09:14.850
regardless if it's on
or off the internet.

00:09:14.850 --> 00:09:17.210
There's always going to be
someone with a different view

00:09:17.210 --> 00:09:17.710
than yours.

00:09:17.710 --> 00:09:20.750
And although I see it as we
don't have the same views,

00:09:20.750 --> 00:09:22.910
I feel like we should
still respect it.

00:09:22.910 --> 00:09:24.370
And some people
don't respect it.

00:09:24.370 --> 00:09:27.040
So whenever I see a troll
or someone like that,

00:09:27.040 --> 00:09:29.090
I feel more sorry
for them because I'm

00:09:29.090 --> 00:09:31.670
like, if you're that
insecure, that's

00:09:31.670 --> 00:09:33.750
why you're fixating
on my life and what

00:09:33.750 --> 00:09:36.230
I'm doing because I
don't go out of my way

00:09:36.230 --> 00:09:37.470
to bring someone down.

00:09:37.470 --> 00:09:40.070
The only time that
you bring someone down

00:09:40.070 --> 00:09:42.624
is when you are
yourself falling,

00:09:42.624 --> 00:09:44.790
which is a struggle that I
feel that they deal with.

00:09:44.790 --> 00:09:46.570
So instead I just ignore them.

00:09:46.570 --> 00:09:49.920
I am fortunate where I don't
have a lot of "haters."

00:09:49.920 --> 00:09:51.930
I don't know if that's
a good or a bad thing,

00:09:51.930 --> 00:09:53.640
because it can bring discussion.

00:09:53.640 --> 00:09:55.010
It can bring awareness.

00:09:55.010 --> 00:09:57.500
And the ones that I
have had, it's just been

00:09:57.500 --> 00:09:59.700
very petty things like, wow.

00:09:59.700 --> 00:10:00.540
You're so gay.

00:10:00.540 --> 00:10:02.740
And I'm like, yeah.

00:10:02.740 --> 00:10:03.500
I am.

00:10:03.500 --> 00:10:05.680
Thank you for that observation.

00:10:05.680 --> 00:10:09.510
But just simply, like, viewing
it as not taking it personally,

00:10:09.510 --> 00:10:11.950
because oftentimes
it's their issue.

00:10:11.950 --> 00:10:13.844
And even in person,
those are the things

00:10:13.844 --> 00:10:15.260
that got to me the
most growing up

00:10:15.260 --> 00:10:17.270
when I was called
slurs in high school

00:10:17.270 --> 00:10:19.940
when I was first out
about my orientation.

00:10:19.940 --> 00:10:22.899
My mom used to always
tell me that in even four

00:10:22.899 --> 00:10:25.440
years from now, four days from
now, it's not going to matter.

00:10:25.440 --> 00:10:27.652
And it's true.

00:10:27.652 --> 00:10:28.860
FEMALE SPEAKER: Very much so.

00:10:28.860 --> 00:10:30.231
Yeah.

00:10:30.231 --> 00:10:31.870
And you bring up your mom.

00:10:31.870 --> 00:10:34.352
Mars, your mother's
here with us today.

00:10:34.352 --> 00:10:35.810
Are there things
that you would say

00:10:35.810 --> 00:10:38.990
to kind of families in order
to-- what advice would you

00:10:38.990 --> 00:10:41.140
give to families
who maybe do have

00:10:41.140 --> 00:10:43.200
children who they don't
necessarily immediately

00:10:43.200 --> 00:10:43.700
understand?

00:10:43.700 --> 00:10:46.127
Like, what resources would
you try and point them to?

00:10:46.127 --> 00:10:48.460
Or what was the thing that
was also most helpful for you

00:10:48.460 --> 00:10:51.114
in dealing with your family
and your coming outs?

00:10:51.114 --> 00:10:52.530
MARS HALLMAN: Well,
one my parents

00:10:52.530 --> 00:10:55.360
were very open to
just listening to me.

00:10:55.360 --> 00:10:59.800
I would introduce a topic, and
whatever they could understand

00:10:59.800 --> 00:11:01.905
for me, you know, my
mom took the initiative

00:11:01.905 --> 00:11:06.750
and would look up GLSEN
or PFLAG resources.

00:11:06.750 --> 00:11:08.510
Just making sure that
your child's safety,

00:11:08.510 --> 00:11:12.780
and respecting your child's
safety, is number one always.

00:11:12.780 --> 00:11:14.950
To make sure that
your questioning

00:11:14.950 --> 00:11:18.710
them is for the benefit of
learning them as a person

00:11:18.710 --> 00:11:20.590
and not for trying
to change them.

00:11:20.590 --> 00:11:22.824
Make sure you're just
learning about them.

00:11:22.824 --> 00:11:24.240
STEPHANIE FROSCH:
My biggest thing

00:11:24.240 --> 00:11:28.050
is, especially-- my dad taught
me this, surprisingly enough.

00:11:28.050 --> 00:11:32.020
My dad is very old school,
but also very accepting.

00:11:32.020 --> 00:11:33.880
But the way that I
see it is I remember

00:11:33.880 --> 00:11:37.160
one time I had my college
roommate coming home after they

00:11:37.160 --> 00:11:39.140
first came out,
and I told my dad,

00:11:39.140 --> 00:11:41.530
you know, they go
by these pronouns.

00:11:41.530 --> 00:11:42.540
This is what you do.

00:11:42.540 --> 00:11:43.910
And he's just nodding along.

00:11:43.910 --> 00:11:46.060
And I asked him, are
you following this?

00:11:46.060 --> 00:11:47.990
And he said, you know,
I don't understand it,

00:11:47.990 --> 00:11:49.780
but that doesn't mean I'm
not going to respect it.

00:11:49.780 --> 00:11:51.380
And that's the way I
feel like it should be.

00:11:51.380 --> 00:11:53.588
You don't have to grasp
something and know everything

00:11:53.588 --> 00:11:55.510
about it right away
to validate a person

00:11:55.510 --> 00:11:57.910
and give them the respect
that they deserve.

00:11:57.910 --> 00:11:59.810
And a big thing that
I've also noticed

00:11:59.810 --> 00:12:03.170
is, especially from when I get
fan mail, a lot of the youth

00:12:03.170 --> 00:12:04.837
say how their parents
don't accept them.

00:12:04.837 --> 00:12:06.878
So that means they're
never going to accept them.

00:12:06.878 --> 00:12:08.410
They don't have
a family anymore.

00:12:08.410 --> 00:12:10.680
Which isn't true
either, and I feel

00:12:10.680 --> 00:12:13.470
like that's important to really
recognize that coming out

00:12:13.470 --> 00:12:15.760
is a process also for the
person hearing the news.

00:12:15.760 --> 00:12:17.660
So my dad, when
I first told him,

00:12:17.660 --> 00:12:20.240
it was very much of a we're not
going to bring this up ever.

00:12:20.240 --> 00:12:22.150
And now my dad is
super supportive.

00:12:22.150 --> 00:12:23.410
And it can change.

00:12:23.410 --> 00:12:24.850
Your parents can change.

00:12:24.850 --> 00:12:26.770
So I know so many
people are quick to say,

00:12:26.770 --> 00:12:28.020
I don't have a family anymore.

00:12:28.020 --> 00:12:28.530
It's done.

00:12:28.530 --> 00:12:30.590
But give them time.

00:12:30.590 --> 00:12:32.820
Parents are close to
perfect in our eyes,

00:12:32.820 --> 00:12:34.570
but everyone has growing room.

00:12:34.570 --> 00:12:37.470
And they can learn from
their children as well.

00:12:37.470 --> 00:12:39.803
FEMALE SPEAKER: I think that's
a wonderful kind of point

00:12:39.803 --> 00:12:43.070
and I think the
whole, it gets better,

00:12:43.070 --> 00:12:45.280
the kind of publicity
and awareness

00:12:45.280 --> 00:12:47.229
that the recent
movements have had

00:12:47.229 --> 00:12:48.770
have definitely been
helpful in that.

00:12:48.770 --> 00:12:51.490
And so it's nice to hear
that there are resources

00:12:51.490 --> 00:12:55.200
and there are outlets for people
who are willing to change.

00:12:55.200 --> 00:12:57.470
And I think everyone has
the capacity to change.

00:12:57.470 --> 00:12:59.240
STEPHANIE FROSCH: Yeah.

00:12:59.240 --> 00:13:00.990
