MARS HALLMAN: I try to make sure
any safe space that I'm part of

00:31:08.100 --> 00:31:10.710
or create is a safe
space for all people.

00:31:10.710 --> 00:31:12.880
But it's important
when you're organizing

00:31:12.880 --> 00:31:15.300
those kind of spaces,
you have your message

00:31:15.300 --> 00:31:16.719
clear from the beginning.

00:31:16.719 --> 00:31:18.260
And make sure everyone
involved knows

00:31:18.260 --> 00:31:21.790
this is a space
for trans rights.

00:31:21.790 --> 00:31:24.870
This is a space for
intersectional feminism.

00:31:24.870 --> 00:31:30.280
This is a place for this group.

00:31:30.280 --> 00:31:31.920
But also make sure
any safe place

00:31:31.920 --> 00:31:34.910
is a safe space universally.

00:31:34.910 --> 00:31:39.040
So as the organizer,
as you, know,

00:31:39.040 --> 00:31:41.159
the moderator, the
organizer, the facilitator,

00:31:41.159 --> 00:31:42.950
it's kind of up to that
person to make sure

00:31:42.950 --> 00:31:47.625
that everything stays
separate and important.

00:31:47.625 --> 00:31:49.750
STEPHANIE FROSCH: What I've
experienced, especially

00:31:49.750 --> 00:31:52.790
at my school, was
when I was bullied

00:31:52.790 --> 00:31:55.796
for being gay, I feel like it
wasn't that I was being bullied

00:31:55.796 --> 00:31:58.170
for being gay, it was just I
was being bullied because it

00:31:58.170 --> 00:31:59.660
was something different.

00:31:59.660 --> 00:32:01.580
So before I was
out, I was made fun

00:32:01.580 --> 00:32:03.740
of because I had a
wheelie backpack.

00:32:03.740 --> 00:32:07.580
And I had a friend who was made
fun of because she hasn't cut

00:32:07.580 --> 00:32:09.000
her hair since she was four.

00:32:09.000 --> 00:32:12.930
And I'm like, whether
I came out as gay

00:32:12.930 --> 00:32:16.000
or I came out as,
you know, a bear,

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:18.930
I would be made fun of
because it was different.

00:32:18.930 --> 00:32:22.677
And especially having a
safe space to go to, which

00:32:22.677 --> 00:32:23.760
I didn't have at the time.

00:32:23.760 --> 00:32:27.700
I know if I did have a GSA, my
entire adolescent experience

00:32:27.700 --> 00:32:30.210
would be completely
different, but online I

00:32:30.210 --> 00:32:32.940
did have those safe spaces and
I did have those resources.

00:32:32.940 --> 00:32:34.900
And I feel like
it is so important

00:32:34.900 --> 00:32:36.840
to continue to grow
these safe spaces

00:32:36.840 --> 00:32:40.367
and to show the entire world no
matter-- because you can come

00:32:40.367 --> 00:32:41.950
out when you're five,
you can come out

00:32:41.950 --> 00:32:43.980
when you're 50,
that no matter what,

00:32:43.980 --> 00:32:45.560
there is a community for you.

00:32:45.560 --> 00:32:47.775
Even if you feel like
you won't fit in even,

00:32:47.775 --> 00:32:49.900
even if you feel like no
one's going to understand,

00:32:49.900 --> 00:32:52.300
there's going to be people who,
even if they don't understand,

00:32:52.300 --> 00:32:53.966
they will listen and
they will be there.

00:32:53.966 --> 00:32:56.770
And that is the most
important thing,

00:32:56.770 --> 00:32:58.350
because you want to
surround yourself

00:32:58.350 --> 00:32:59.800
with people who
listen, not people

00:32:59.800 --> 00:33:02.488
who throw you down and
don't let you be heard.

00:33:04.739 --> 00:33:06.780
FEMALE SPEAKER: Thank you
so much for being here.

00:33:06.780 --> 00:33:10.270
Thank you for being excellent
advocates and activists

00:33:10.270 --> 00:33:11.990
and just beacons of positivity.

00:33:11.990 --> 00:33:13.615
So let's give them
a round of applause.

00:33:13.615 --> 00:33:15.450
STEPHANIE FROSCH: Thank
you for having us.

